<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-100-283 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 032 459</DOCID><JOURNAL>InfoWorld  July 29 1991 v13 n30 p14(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Transition to DOS 5.0 is proving to be as painless as promised.andO;(User Reaction)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Johnston, Stuart J.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Most users are experiencing little difficulty upgrading toMicrosoft's new MS-DOS 5.0 operating system, despite some minorcompatibility problems.andP;  Users report that the transition isproceeding smoothly, although initial demand made copies of theprogram difficult to obtain and support technicians difficult toreach.andP;  One user says that his company has experienced no majorproblems after installing DOS 5.0 on a few of its 70microcomputers.andP;  Another has decided to upgrade after determiningthat DOS 5.0's better memory management is worth its addedcomplexity.andP;  One large user with 1,000 microcomputers plans a'slow upgrade.' A consultant and value-added reseller says thatabout 30 to 40 percent of the systems he sells are being shippedwith DOS 5.0.andP;  Both Microsoft and consultants report a deluge oftechnical support calls.andP;  The software giant has already shippedmore than 1 million copies of DOS 5.0.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Microsoft Corp. (Products).andO;Ticker:    MSFT.andO;Product:   MS-DOS 5.0 (Operating system) (Usage).andO;Topic:     Operating systemsUpgradingUser NeedsImplementationCompatibilityUser Survey.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>